ton_beach_datasheet.csv'\ndf = pd.read_csv(sheet_path, skiprows=1, header=[0, 1])\n\n# Flatten 2-row header\ncols = df.columns.to_frame(index=False)\ncols[0] = cols[0].replace(r'^Unnamed.*', pd.NA, regex=True).ffill()\nflat_cols = []\nfor a, b in cols.itertuples(index=False):\n    parts = [str(x).strip() for x in (a, b) if pd.notna(x) and str(x).strip() and str(x).strip().lower() != 'nan']\n    flat_cols.append('_'.join(parts))\ndf.columns = flat_cols\n\n# Reshape Tag/Enterococcus columns into tidy long format\nvalue_cols = [c for c in df.columns if 'Tag' in c or 'Enterococcus' in c]\nid_cols = [c for c in df.columns if c not in value_cols]\nlong_df = df.melt(id_vars=id_cols, value_vars=value_cols, var_name='Variable', value_name='Value')\nlong_df['Location'] = long_df['Variable'].str.split('_').str[0]\nlong_df['Measure'] = long_df['Variable'].str.split('_').str[1]\ntidy = long_df.pivot(index=id_cols + ['Location'], columns='Measure', values='Value').reset_index()\ntidy.columns.name = None\n\n# Numeric conversion\nfor col in tidy.columns:\n    if col not in id_cols + ['Location', 'Tag']:\n        tidy[col] = pd.to_numeric(tidy[col], errors='coerce')\n\n# Use 2023 rows only if year can be inferred from Date\nif 'Date' in tidy.columns:\n    years = pd.to_datetime(tidy['Date'], errors='coerce').dt.year\n    tidy = tidy[years.eq(2023)].copy()\n\n# Apply tag rules: '<x' -> x/2, '>x' -> x, exact x unchanged\ntag = tidy['Tag'].astype(str).str.strip()\ntidy.loc[tag.eq('<'), 'Enterococcus'] = tidy.loc[tag.eq('<'), 'Enterococcus'] / 2\n\ncorr = tidy['3-Day Rain'].corr(tidy['Enterococcus'], method='pearson')\nprint(f'{corr:.3f}')", "reason": "Rewrote the solution to follow the available authored plan exactly: derive Boston Harbor beach names, EJ municipalities >90%, identify the qualifying beach from 2023 marine testing records, then compute Pearson correlation from the authored Wollaston datasheet using the documented two-row header parsing and tag handling. The code prints t